      <hedline>
        <hl1>Quality-of-Life Crisis</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Myrna Greenberg letter notes that City Lights Youth Theater, which she founded in 1991, has been seeking studio and office space for over year, after being forced out of space by rent increases</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There is indeed a real estate crisis in New York City (front page, Sept. 19), but it is not limited to the business world. Nonprofit groups are also affected.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>There is indeed a real estate crisis in New York City (front page, Sept. 19), but it is not limited to the business world. Nonprofit groups are also affected.</p>
        <p>City Lights Youth Theater, which I founded in 1991, has been seeking studio and office space for more than a year, after being forced out of a space by rent increases. How will nonprofit groups like ours survive without a government or private subsidy?</p>
        <p>City Lights provides in-school and after-school theater education for nearly 2,000 children. Losing groups like ours could lead to another kind of exodus from the city, as people seek a better quality of life.</p>
        <p>Developers and urban planners are right to seek a ''concerted effort on the part of the city's political leaders.'' We hope those leaders will put nonprofit groups on that agenda.</p>
        <p>MYRNA GREENBERG  New York, Sept. 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
